{
  "title": "Schools of Tool-Making",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "059bd2ba7dc9462e",
      "text": "In \"Tools for conviviality\" [12], Ivan Illich describes two schools of tool-making, the means by which humans influence their environment. *Manipulative* tools focus on immediate productivity. They use and build upon what is readily available and convenient to use. Little attention is paid to the process by which tools are created, leading to deep chains of dependence on tools that require other tools to be built. Over time, special interests hijack the apparatus of tool creation and management. Deficiencies in certain tools are papered over with other tools. What used to be a means to another end gradually becomes an end in itself, the production and maintenance of which requires more and more manpower, from people who are not motivated to cooperate in this endeavor and who therefore need more and more management.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "6aa4ad5c92cba558",
      "text": "In response, Illich proposes an alternative school he calls *convivial* tools. In his view, the main goal in developing a tool should not be to make a particular tactical activity more convenient. Instead, it should be about preserving the individual's degrees of freedom as we explore alternative combinations of human and machine. Individuals should decide for themselves what they use their own labor for. We should celebrate tools that preserve individual agency and shun tools that limit human agency. Specifically, if one tool doesn't quite do what you need it to do, you shouldn't try to cover up its shortcomings with a second tool. The maintenance required for both will result in more and more demands on your time and the time of others, reducing the degree of freedom of human society as a whole. Instead, take *out* the first tool and rethink the problem."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "4c3dd2bca858db49",
      "text": "It is difficult to remove tools from existing workflows. Our social arrangements tend to take artifacts for granted once they have been introduced (and have experienced a certain level of acceptance). People who have grown up in our society tend to expect a certain degree of specialization, with problems being partitioned according to fairly static boundaries. Most people's careers are limited by these boundaries. When we get used to something we don't know how to build or manage, the prospect of losing it is painful."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "140a1e287ef218c8",
      "text": "If we assume that Illich's goal is desirable, the problem becomes how to promote greater dissemination of knowledge about tools. How can we develop tools that can be maintained by end users in the field without the support of authors and experts?"
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "0289573b972369ab",
