        "id": "6aa4ad5c92cba558",
        "text": "In response, Illich proposes an alternative school he calls \"convivial tools.\" In his view, the main goal in developing a tool should not be to make a particular tactical activity more convenient. Instead, it should be about preserving the individual's degrees of freedom as we explore alternative combinations of man and machine. Individuals should decide for themselves what they use their own labor for. We should celebrate tools that preserve individual agency and shun tools that limit human agency. Specifically, if one tool doesn't quite do what you need it to do, you shouldn't try to cover up its shortcomings with a second tool. The maintenance required for both will result in more and more demands on your time and the time of others, reducing the degree of freedom of human society as a whole. Instead, take out the first tool and rethink the problem."
